a, which is formed with the Old Norse personal name <i>Halfdan</i>, these placenames all consist of an Old English personal name + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, for example <i>Ælfsige</i> in the case of Alstone in Gloucestershire."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert de Aston was born in 1100, in Cheshire, England, his father, Richard de Aston, was 13 and his mother, Sarah, was 11. He had at least 1 son with Mary of Sutton. He died in 1160, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1100–1160":"1100–1160","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","1109–Male":"1109–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1132–1195":"1132–1195","1088–Male":"1088–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","1105":"1105","1100":"1100","Abt 1110":"umbes 1110","1088":"1088","1132":"1132","1195":"1195","about 1132":"umbes 1132","1160":"1160","1109":"1109","England":"Inglismaa, Unite